notes: Max Homa earned his first PGA TOUR victory at the Wells Fargo Championship, defeating Joel Dahmen by three shots with a score of 15-under 269. The victory came in his 69th start at the age of 28 years, 5 months, 16 days.
Through 54 holes, Max Homa was tied with Joel Dahmen and Jason Dufner for the lead at 11-under 202. The share of the lead represented Homa's first after any round on the PGA TOUR.
Max Homa became the fifth player to make the Wells Fargo Championship his first career victory, joining Anthony Kim (2008), Rory McIlroy (2010), Rickie Fowler (2012) and Derek Ernst (2013).
Max Homa led the field in Strokes Gained:Putting with an average of 2.472 per round, averaging more than two strokes in that category for the first time on TOUR.

Joel Dahmen collected his first solo-second finish on the PGA TOUR, with his previous-best result coming at the 2018 John Deere Classic (T2). With an opening 66, Dahmen held a share of the 18-hole lead, his third such lead in a seven-week stretch on TOUR (Valspar Championship, Corales Puntacana Resort & Club Championship, Wells Fargo Championship).
With his third-place result, Justin Rose earned his third consecutive top-five at the Wells Fargo Championship (5th/2014, 3rd/2016, 3rd/2019; DNP in 2015, 2017, 2018).
2010 and 2015 Wells Fargo Championship winner Rory McIlroy held a share of the 18-hole lead en route to a T8 result.
Defending champion Jason Day finished T24 at 4-under 280 in his bid to become the first player to win back-to-back titles at the Wells Fargo Championship.
